metadata.name: SkeleSteamPunx #90
metadata.description:
Genesis generative image project by @LimnDigital.

65 total unique traits = 2,459,688 possible variations (including backgrounds and base)
52 skull/facial traits = 111,804 possible variations. 
Each trait created via custom VQGAN+CLIP Python code by LimnDigital.
Each trait isolated and manually extracted in Procreate, then randomly assembled via p5.js and custom JavaScript by LimnDigital.

Not associated with Larva Labs, CryptoPunks, or any ‘Skulls’ or ‘Punks’ projects. 

Save your minted Artwork (or any edition) in Live Mode by pressing:
‘s’ or ‘S’ to save at current canvas size.
‘f’ or ‘F’ to save at Full size, 2048 x 2048px.
‘t’ or ‘T’ to save at Twitter Tweet size, 1200 x 1200px.

Saved Artwork filename contains: Project Name, Artist Name, Pixel size, and Unique Hash.

metadata.name: aprendizajes #38
metadata.description:
aprendizajes is a generative art project that pays a tribute to the process of learning. 25% of primary proceeds go to Save The Children. Full description of the artwork+instructions here: https://www.iillucid.com/aprendizajes/

The artwork allows the user to:

* Change resolution: press 'd' followed by any number from 1 to 9 to add that amount to the pixel density. If you get a black screen you have surpassed what your graphics card can handle: press d + 0 to reset the pixel density. You can fine tune pressing d followed by + or - (+/- 0.5).
* Save image: press 's' to save the current image as png. For a higher resolution png, 1st increase the resolution using 'd' and then save the image with 's'.
* Tune image parameters: press 'z' (brightness), 'x' (contrast), 'g' (gamma), 'b' (blur) followed by + or - to adjust. Toggle tuning with 'a'. Press 'n' then + or - to adjust amount of noise.
* Redraw: 'r' (changes how lines are drawn)

It is recommended to read the full instructions on the article.

metadata.name: Celebrations #65
metadata.description:
Celebration is a presentation of colors, patterns, and flow fields into a beautiful arrangement. The algorithm's core consists of a flow field packed with circles on top without collisions between themselves and the edges. Patterns are then drawn on top of the circles using Sayama's p5.pattern library.  I hope we take this holiday season to celebrate our little wins and successes with gratitude and enjoy what we have.

For flow field lovers, check out my study on flow fields at http://www.theflo.xyz/

metadata.name: Ribbonacci #115
metadata.description:
Interlocking ribbons are placed around focal points like sunflower seeds, using the Golden angle.

Features: six color schemes, two color variation types, three rendering styles, and variable aspect ratios.

----

The Golden angle is based on φ ("phi"), the most irrational number. Using this angle between successive ribbons means that as they spiral outwards, they end up distributed evenly around the center. The Golden angle is visible in many plants, not just the sunflower, since it helps prevent leaves from shading each other. ("Fibonacci phyllotaxis")

Phi, the Golden angle, and Fibonacci numbers generally have many fascinating, unexpected, and beautiful mathematical and geometric relationships. Learning about them was a delight.

----

Keys: 1-8 to change pixel density, s or double click to save, S to toggle drop shadows if present.
URL parameters: shadows (0 or 1), animated (0 or 1), aspect (e.g. 16:9, 2:3, 8.5:11)

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #221
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash
